## Pedagogical Approaches

### Use of Primary Sources

The lesson emphasizes the analysis of authentic historical documents, including photographs, speeches, broadsides, and political cartoons. This approach fosters critical thinking and helps students connect emotionally and intellectually with the historical actors ([Library of Congress, n.d.](https://www.loc.gov/classroom-materials/suffragists-and-their-tactics/)).

### Interactive and Collaborative Learning

Students work in pairs or small groups to analyze sources and discuss their findings, promoting peer learning and communication skills. Activities such as timeline creation and museum exhibits encourage creativity and deeper engagement ([Putnam History Museum, n.d.](https://www.putnamhistorymuseum.org/education/womens-suffrage-lesson-plan/)).

### Cross-Disciplinary Connections

The lesson integrates history with civics, gender studies, and social justice themes, helping students understand the multifaceted nature of suffrage and its ongoing relevance ([Truman Library, n.d.](https://www.trumanlibrary.gov/education/lesson-plans/women-and-world-war-one)).

---

## Key Historical Facts and Figures

- **Women’s Workforce Participation:** From 1916 onward, women filled labor shortages in factories, farms, and offices, marking a significant social shift ([Oak National Academy, 2025](https://www.thenational.academy/teachers/programmes/history-secondary-ks3/units/womens-suffrage-what-do-sources-tell-us-about-womens-struggle-for-equality/lessons/the-contribution-of-women-during-ww1)).

- **Army Nurse Corps:** Over 20,000 women served, with 10,000 deployed overseas, often near front lines and under hazardous conditions ([World War I Centennial Commission, 2022](https://www.worldwar1centennial.org/index.php/communicate/press-media/wwi-centennial-news/4205-women-in-world-war-i-education-resources.html)).

- **Legislative Milestones:**
  - 1918 Representation of the People Act: Granted voting rights to all men and women over 30 who met property qualifications.
  - 1928 Equal Franchise Act: Extended voting rights to all women aged 21 and over, achieving full electoral equality with men ([Oak National Academy, 2025](https://www.thenational.academy/teachers/programmes/history-secondary-ks3/units/womens-suffrage-what-do-sources-tell-us-about-womens-struggle-for-equality/lessons/the-contribution-of-women-during-ww1)).

- **Political Endorsement:** President Woodrow Wilson’s 1918 statement acknowledged women’s war contributions and supported their right to vote, reflecting a shift in public and political opinion ([World War I Centennial Commission, 2022](https://www.worldwar1centennial.org/index.php/communicate/press-media/wwi-centennial-news/4205-women-in-world-war-i-education-resources.html)).

